    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-31T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-31T11:00:00-05:00" n="622"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d622">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1837</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-31T17:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 31, 1915, 5 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 1, 7.20 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2337. <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName> gave to United Press
                    to-day an interview implying Germany will not give up its method of submarine
                    warfare. He also quoted from autobiography of ex-Ambassador <persName>Andrew D.
                        White</persName>, volume II, page 168, when White says at his request during
                    our Spanish war German Government stopped and searched steamer supposed to be
                    sailing with arms for Spain. In this connection please note German Government
                    was probably quite ready to oblige white, as he practically offered them a gift
                    of part of the Philippine Islands. See his 494, July 13, 1898, and 507, July 30,
                    1898, to Department, and Department’s 556 of August 15, 1898, to him.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
